## Questions-First Protocol
- Before generating documentation on **any new major topic**, share the plan and ask quick calibration questions inline
- Log calibration answers in `questions/[topic].md` for future reference
- User prefers to **jump in** rather than fill out questionnaires — keep questions minimal and actionable

## User Preferences (learned from feedback)
- **Code language**: Kotlin only (modern, what Google expects)
- **Style**: Jump-in learner — start building docs, refine as we go
- **Depth**: L6/Staff level — always cover what a junior would miss
- **IPC / Binder deep-dive**: Completed as `docs/ipc-binder/` series
- **Memory & Performance deep-dive**: Completed as `docs/memory-performance/` series
- **Lifecycle & Navigation deep-dive**: Completed as `docs/lifecycle-navigation/` series
- **Testing & DI deep-dive**: Completed as `docs/testing-di/` series
- **System Services & Platform Internals deep-dive**: Completed as `docs/system-services/` series
- **View System deep-dive**: Completed as `docs/view-system/` series

## Content Standards (L6 Bar)
- Cover **internals**, not just APIs — explain *why* and *how* things work under the hood
- Include **trade-offs**, **gotchas**, and **Google-scale considerations**
- Reference **AOSP internals** where relevant
- Cover **Jetpack Compose** alongside the View system where applicable
- Include **interview-style Q&A** sections at the end of each doc
- All code examples in **Kotlin**

## Do NOT
- Dump everything in one file
- Use generic/tutorial-level explanations
- Skip diagrams for complex topics (threading, IPC, rendering pipeline, etc.)
- Block on lengthy questionnaires — ask quick questions inline, then proceed
